Best solution: EventBridge Lambda warmer + Aurora min_capacity bump.
Deploy both together. Here's why this combination and not one of the alternatives.
Why this over the alternatives:

Not Provisioned Concurrency alone — expensive, and doesn't fix Aurora warm-up (which is your bigger cost: 6.4s query vs 900ms Lambda init). Would burn money for partial win.
Not Aurora bump alone — Lambda cold-start (~900ms + 500ms IAM token = 1.4s) still eats most of your budget even before the DB gets involved.
Not warmer alone — keeps Lambda warm but Aurora can still cold-scale on the query side.
Both together — attacks both cold-start sources for < $10/month total in dev. Best cost-to-effect ratio.

What this looks like in practice:

EventBridge rule invokes the Lambda every 5 minutes with a tiny warmup payload.
Lambda handler recognizes the warmup and does a light DB touch (SELECT 1), then returns immediately. Keeps Lambda container warm AND Aurora buffer cache active.
Aurora min_capacity = 2 (up from 1). Keeps Aurora warmer floor so compute doesn't scale down between pings.

When KIVS calls:

Lambda container is already initialized → skip ~900ms cold-start.
Aurora is warm and cached → skip 5–6 seconds of query warm-up.
Expected result: cold calls land around 0.5–1.0s. Comfortably under 2s.

